Analysis of onomatopoeias

Bodo

16/11/2020

1 Introduction

This analysis will focus on the onomatopoeias, and using the full dataset thats available as no hand annotation is required.

2 Setup

Load packages:

library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext) # for unnest_tokens()
library(brms)
library(wordcloud) # for word cloud

Get all file names:

birds <- read_csv('../data/birds_master_file_annotated_12_02_25.csv')
## Warning: One or more parsing issues, call `problems()` on your data frame for details,
## e.g.:

3 Onomatopoeia and word count analyses

Count onomatopoeias and warblishes:

birds <- mutate(birds,
                onom_count = str_count(voice, '\\".+?\\"'),
                warblish_count = str_count(voice, '\\*.+?\\*'))

Count the words and add a count variable:

word_counts <- birds |> 
  unnest_tokens(word, voice) |> 
  count(unique_id) |> 
  rename(word_count = n)

Join that back in:

birds <- left_join(birds, word_counts)
## Joining with `by = join_by(unique_id)`

Plot of onomatopoeia count with word count:

birds |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = onom_count, y = word_count)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_classic()
## Warning: Removed 172 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

Create a has onomatopoeia / has no onomatopoeia variable and see whether we can make more sense of that:

birds <- mutate(birds,
                has_onom = if_else(onom_count > 0, 'has onomatopoeia', 'no onomatopoeia'))

Check word counts for those:

birds |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = has_onom, y = word_count, fill = has_onom)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c('goldenrod3', 'purple', 'darkgrey')) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')

So, if there is an onomatopoeia its also a longer text. I guess this makes sense if whats happening here is that some fieldguides just generally have more info, and theyre also going to contain more onomatopoeias.

4 Individualizing onomatopoeia patterns

4.1 Extract onomatopoeia

Extract onomatopoeias and warblish:

# Extract onomatopoeias:

birds$onoms <- sapply(str_extract_all(birds$voice, '\\".+?\\"'),
                      function(x) str_c(x, collapse = '_'))

Create an onomatopoeia-free version of the text to see if we can compare things to the typographically unmarked ones:

birds <- mutate(birds,
                voice_reduced = str_replace_all(voice_reduced, '\\".+?\\"', ''),
                voice_reduced = str_replace_all(voice_reduced, '\\*.+?\\*', ''))

4.2 Preceding character

Get the directly preceding character:

birds$preceding_char <- sapply(
  str_match_all(birds$voice, '(\\S)\\s*\\".+?\\"'), 
  function(x) str_c(x[,2], collapse = '_')
  )

Check if theres any where the separator counts dont match:

birds |>
  filter(!(str_count(onoms, '_') == str_count(preceding_char, '_'))) |>
  select(onoms, preceding_char, voice)
## # A tibble: 47  3
##    onoms                                                    preceding_char voice
##    <chr>                                                    <chr>          <chr>
##  1 "\"Tchink, tchink, tchink\"_\"tchook\""                  k              "\"T
##  2 "\"zip\"_\"churt\"_\"chim\"_\"cheedle cheedle chee?\"_\ e_,_,_y        "Bel
##  3 "\"woo-hoo\"_\"hoo-hoo-hoo\""                            o              "\"w
##  4 "\"Chicky-whew\"_\"chee-lick\""                          w              "\"C
##  5 "\"too-li\"_\"coo-eep\""                                 i              "\"t
##  6 "\"Tserp-tserp\"_\"pi-pi-pi...\""                        p              "\"T
##  7 "\"chew-ich\"_\"aach\""                                  h              "\"c
##  8 "\"Churrr, churrr, churrr\"_\"chirriree\"_\"keereereek\ r_e            "\"C
##  9 "\"tac tac\"_\"cherr\""                                  c              "\"t
## 10 "\"Tchack tchak\"_\"terr terr\"_\"see-ip\""              k_r            "\"T
## #  37 more rows

This is whenever the onomatopoeia is first. So, lets append an empty space before that with the separator (these are all multi-onomatopoeia entries):

fixed_preceding_chars <- birds |>
  filter(!(str_count(onoms, '_') == str_count(preceding_char, '_'))) |>
  select(onoms, preceding_char, voice) |> 
  mutate(preceding_char = str_c(' _', preceding_char)) |> 
  pull(preceding_char)

And add that back into the data:

# Get offending rows:

rows_to_fix <- !(str_count(birds$onoms, '_') == str_count(birds$preceding_char, '_'))
rows_to_fix <- which(rows_to_fix)

# Re-add the fixed strings:

birds[rows_to_fix, ]$preceding_char <- fixed_preceding_chars

Check now that its the correct number each time:

birds |> 
  filter(!(str_count(onoms, '_') == str_count(preceding_char, '_')))
## # A tibble: 0  31
## #  31 variables: unique_id <chr>, fieldguide <chr>, english_common <chr>,
## #   latin_species <chr>, length <chr>, order <chr>, family <chr>,
## #   family_english <chr>, voice <chr>, warblish <chr>, usable <chr>,
## #   voice_reduced <chr>, non_vocalization <chr>, distance_amplitude <chr>,
## #   namesake <chr>, qualifies_as_song <lgl>, mimicry <chr>, comparison <chr>,
## #   comparison_type <chr>, comparison_expression <chr>, comparand <chr>,
## #   comp_construction <chr>, comp_dimension <chr>,

Woohoo, it is!

4.3 Following character

Lets get the last character now:

birds$following_char <- sapply(
  str_match_all(birds$voice, '\\".+?\\"\\s*(\\S)'), 
  function(x) str_c(x[,2], collapse = '_')
)

Check when they dont align:

birds |> 
  filter(!(str_count(onoms, '_') == str_count(following_char, '_'))) |> 
  pull(voice)
## [1] "Flight call a coarse \"grrrt\"; lower single note \"dirp\" like Western Meadowlark; also a coarse, grating \"ji ji ji ji ji\"; In courtship a low, soft moan very similar to distant cow mooing; Flight song a rapidly repeated, wild, harsh whistle \"we we we we we...\""                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              
## [2] "Sharp \"scaap\" when flushed and a musical \"chippa-chippa-chippa\""                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
## [3] "Bell's Vireo has numerous calls. Most often heard is a fast, nasal, scolding alarm call, which sounds wrenlike. Other calls associated with conflict or contact include \"zip\", \"churt\", \"chim\", and a high, piercing squeal. The primary song is a hurried, scratchy \"cheedle cheedle chee?\" \"cheedle cheedle chew!\"--easily remembered by its two-part structure, a rising question followed by a definitive answer. Males sing incessantly during the breeding season, females very rarely. Young male Bell's Vireos also give a quiet, rambling version of the song late in the breeding season, almost as if practicing their singing. This is true of many vireo species."
## [4] "loud, ringing calls that reverberate from rock walls of gorges. Many variations, often beginning with high, clear, drawn out, rising whistles, quickly followed by abrupt, rich, mellow, at times bubbling notes. Among these: \"pieeer-pieeer, chokka-chok-chok\"; \"wheeeit-wheeeit, quorr-quorr-quorr, queet-queeet\"; also, long descending trill, single, quick \"cheewhip!\""                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      
## [5] "A harsh \"jeet\" is the most commonly heard call, usually from flying or feeding birds. They make various distress, alarm, and contact calls mostly on the breeding grounds. Displaying males sing a brief song that begins with a high, thin, rising \"te-e-e-e-e\" \"tweer-tweer-tweer\" and closes with a falling, buzzy trill."

Ok, essentially just two offending patterns, which are either the onomatopoeia is last, as in 1 and 2, or theres just a space and then the next onomatopoeia already starts, with nothing intervening.

Get these offending rows:

rows_to_fix <- !(str_count(birds$onoms, '_') == str_count(birds$following_char, '_'))
rows_to_fix <- which(rows_to_fix)

THen well fix these by hand - its only a couple cases anyway:

birds[rows_to_fix, ]$following_char <- c(';_l_;_ ',
                                         'w_ ',
                                         ',_,_,_ _-',
                                         ';_;_ ',
                                         'i_ _a')

4.4 Extract preceding word

Extract preceding word:

birds$preceding_word <- sapply(
  str_match_all(birds$voice, '(?:(\\b\\S+)\\s+)?\\".+?\\"'), 
  function(x) str_c(ifelse(is.na(x[,2]), "", x[,2]), collapse = '_')
)

Now, check if theres any mismatching numbers:

filter(birds,
       !(str_count(preceding_word, '_') == str_count(onoms, '_')))
## # A tibble: 0  33
## #  33 variables: unique_id <chr>, fieldguide <chr>, english_common <chr>,
## #   latin_species <chr>, length <chr>, order <chr>, family <chr>,
## #   family_english <chr>, voice <chr>, warblish <chr>, usable <chr>,
## #   voice_reduced <chr>, non_vocalization <chr>, distance_amplitude <chr>,
## #   namesake <chr>, qualifies_as_song <lgl>, mimicry <chr>, comparison <chr>,
## #   comparison_type <chr>, comparison_expression <chr>, comparand <chr>,
## #   comp_construction <chr>, comp_dimension <chr>,

None, perfect.

birds$following_word <- sapply(
  str_match_all(birds$voice, '\\".+?\\"\\s+(\\b\\S+)?'),
  function(x) str_c(ifelse(is.na(x[,2]), "", x[,2]), collapse = '_')
)

Check that its the same number:

filter(birds,
       !(str_count(following_word, '_') == str_count(onoms, '_')))

4.5 Put onomatopoeias into long format

Get only the rows we need:

onoms_only <- birds |>
  select(unique_id, voice, onoms, preceding_char, preceding_word, following_char)

Make it into long format:

onoms_long <- onoms_only |> 
  separate_longer_delim(c(onoms, preceding_char, preceding_word, following_char),
                        delim = '_')

# Change order:

onoms_long <- onoms_long |>
  select(unique_id, voice, preceding_char, following_char, preceding_word, onoms) |> 
  rename(onomatopoeia = onoms)

# Fill empty rows with NAs:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     preceding_char = if_else(preceding_char == '', NA, preceding_char),
                     following_char = if_else(following_char == '', NA, following_char),
                     preceding_word = if_else(preceding_word == '', NA, preceding_word),
                     onomatopoeia = if_else(onomatopoeia == '', NA, onomatopoeia))

4.6 Get rid of quotes

Now lets get rid of the quotes:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     onomatopoeia = str_replace_all(onomatopoeia, '\"', ''))

4.7 Extract for hand annotation

For hand-annotation, well create two extra columns:

# onoms_long$phono_legal <- NA
# onoms_long$complex_onset <- NA

Write it to file outside of R:

# write_csv(onoms_long,
#           '../data/onomatopoeias_all_extracted.csv')

5 Syntactic explorations

5.1 Onomatopoeia length and sentence position

Calculate the length of the onomatopoeias:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     length = str_count(onomatopoeia, '.'))

Check what precedes:

onoms_long |> 
  count(preceding_char, sort = TRUE) |>
  print(n = Inf)
## # A tibble: 41  2
##    preceding_char     n
##    <chr>          <int>
##  1 <NA>            2224
##  2 "g"             1373
##  3 "d"             1246
##  4 "r"             1015
##  5 "e"              791
##  6 ","              587
##  7 "l"              563
##  8 "t"              513
##  9 "p"              451
## 10 "y"              417
## 11 "s"              412
## 12 "h"              344
## 13 ":"              244
## 14 "c"              166
## 15 "a"              152
## 16 "w"              143
## 17 "n"              142
## 18 "f"              122
## 19 "o"              108
## 20 "k"               84
## 21 ";"               77
## 22 " "               47
## 23 "z"               30

## 26 "m"               15
## 27 "("               13
## 28 "5"                5

Any letter or number is within the sentence:

onoms_long <- onoms_long |>
  mutate(pre_isolation = if_else(preceding_char %in% letters,
                                 'in sentence', preceding_char),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation %in% LETTERS,
                                 'in sentence', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation %in% as.character(0:9),
                                 'in sentence', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == ' ',
                                 'starts sentence', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == '.',
                                 'starts sentence', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == '(',
                                 'in brackets', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == '-',
                                 'after hyphen', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == ';',
                                 'after semicolon', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == ':',
                                 'after colon', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation == ',',
                                 'after comma', pre_isolation),
         pre_isolation = if_else(pre_isolation %in% c("=", "'", ")"),
                                 NA, pre_isolation))

Check word count as a function of what comes before:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_isolation)) |> 
  filter(pre_isolation != 'in brackets') |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(pre_isolation, length), y = log(length),
             fill = pre_isolation)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(direction = -1,
                    palette = 'YlGnBu') +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.6) +
  xlab(NULL) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        legend.position = 'none')

# Save:

ggsave('../figures/onomatopoeia_length_by_sentence.pdf',
       width = 4.5, height = 4)

5.2 Whether its a word and sentence position

Get the CMU data:

CMU <- readLines('../data/CMU_dict-0.7b.txt')
CMU <- CMU[-c(1:126)] # only metadata
CMU <- str_split(CMU, pattern = ' +')
words <- sapply(CMU, FUN = function(x) x[1])
words <- str_to_lower(words)

Check which of the onomatopoeias are also a word:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     is_also_word = if_else(onomatopoeia %in% words,
                                            'is also a word', 'is not a word'))

How many of these?

onoms_long |> 
  count(is_also_word)
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   is_also_word       n
##   <chr>          <int>
## 1 is also a word  1119
## 2 is not a word  10237

Cool, lets see if any patterns emerge:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_isolation)) |> 
  count(pre_isolation, is_also_word) |> 
  group_by(pre_isolation) |> 
  mutate(p = n / sum(n))
## # A tibble: 13  4
## # Groups:   pre_isolation [7]
##    pre_isolation   is_also_word       n      p
##    <chr>           <chr>          <int>  <dbl>
##  1 after colon     is also a word     3 0.0123
##  2 after colon     is not a word    241 0.988 
##  3 after comma     is also a word    24 0.0409
##  4 after comma     is not a word    563 0.959 
##  5 after hyphen    is not a word     19 1     
##  6 after semicolon is also a word     2 0.0260
##  7 after semicolon is not a word     75 0.974 
##  8 in brackets     is also a word     5 0.385 
##  9 in brackets     is not a word      8 0.615 
## 10 in sentence     is also a word  1077 0.133 
## 11 in sentence     is not a word   7035 0.867 
## 12 starts sentence is also a word     5 0.0685
## 13 starts sentence is not a word     68 0.932

Make a plot of this:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_isolation)) |>
  filter(pre_isolation != 'in brackets') |> 
  count(pre_isolation, is_also_word) |> 
  group_by(pre_isolation) |> 
  mutate(p = n / sum(n)) |> 
  filter(is_also_word == 'is also a word') |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(pre_isolation, p), y = p,
             fill = reorder(pre_isolation, p))) +
  geom_col(col = 'black',
           width = 0.6) +
  scale_fill_brewer(direction = +1,
                    palette = 'YlGnBu') +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0),
                     limits = c(0, 0.2)) +
  xlab(NULL) +
  ylab('p(is also a word)') +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = 'none',
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

ggsave('../figures/syntactic_isolation_and_dictionary_word_match.pdf',
       width = 4.5, height = 3.5)

5.3 Whether it has repeated consonants

Count the repeated consonants:

onoms_long <- onoms_long |> 
  mutate(repeated_consonants = str_count(onomatopoeia, "(?i)([b-df-hj-np-tv-z])\\1+"))

Cool. Lets make a variable out of this that just codes for whether it has repeated consonants or not:

onoms_long <- onoms_long |> 
  mutate(has_repeated = if_else(repeated_consonants > 1, 'has letter replication', 'no letter replication'))

Check this as a function of syntax:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_isolation)) |> 
  count(pre_isolation, has_repeated) |> 
  group_by(pre_isolation) |> 
  mutate(p = n / sum(n))
## # A tibble: 13  4

Make a plot of this:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_isolation)) |>

Make a simplified plot:

# Simplified syntactic isolation variable:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     syntax_red = if_else(pre_isolation %in% c('after colon',
                                                               'after semicolon'),
                                          'after juncture', NA),
                     syntax_red = if_else(pre_isolation %in% c('starts sentence',
                                                               'in sentence'),
                                          'in sentence', syntax_red))

# Check:

onoms_long |> 
  count(syntax_red) |>

Make a plot of this:

  filter(!is.na(syntax_red)) |> 
  count(syntax_red, has_repeated) |> 
  group_by(syntax_red) |> 
  mutate(p = n / sum(n)) |>

  theme_classic() +

        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0.5),

6 Frequency of onomatopoeias

Compute frequency of onomatopoeias:

# Count:

onom_freq <- onoms_long |> 
  count(onomatopoeia, sort = TRUE) |> 
  filter(!is.na(onomatopoeia))

# Show:

onom_freq
## # A tibble: 6,916  2
##    onomatopoeia     n

6.1 Frequency and typographic marking

See whether these also occur in the typographically unmarked positions. For this we can simply collapse the entire voice_reduced column into a text and then just grep out of it.

To make sure that we dont match parts of words, well add spaces around:

all_text <- str_c(filter(birds, !is.na(voice_reduced))$voice_reduced, collapse = ' ')

# Append a word start and word finish:

onom_freq <- mutate(onom_freq,
                    onomatopoeia = str_c(' ', onomatopoeia, ' '))

# Empty column:

onom_freq$unmarked_freq <- 0

# Loop through and add count:

for (i in 1:nrow(onom_freq)) {
  onom_freq[i, ]$unmarked_freq <- onom_freq[i, ]$unmarked_freq +
    str_count(all_text, onom_freq[i, ]$onomatopoeia)
  
  if (i %% 1000 == 0) {
    cat(str_c("hello outside-loop world, I'm iteration ", i, '\n'))
  }
}

# Save:

save(onom_freq, file = '../models/onom_freq.RData')

Load:

load('../models/onom_freq.RData')

Check:

## 10 " pik "         22             0 no unmarked                    
## #  6,906 more rows

Create a has typographically unmarked version:

onom_freq <- mutate(onom_freq,
                    has_unmarked = if_else(unmarked_freq > 0, 'occurs typographically unmarked', 'no unmarked'))

Get rid of trailing spaces again, which we only embedded to ensure matching within the sentence.

onom_freq <- mutate(onom_freq,
                    onomatopoeia = str_trim(onomatopoeia))

Now we can get rid of those onomatopoeias that have spaces or hyphens in them. These are multisyllabic and it would be unfair / biasing towards what I want to show to keep in them analysis since theyre never going to occur typographically unmarked again anyway, being essentially full phrases.

So we should restrict things to the monosyllabic stuff.

onom_freq_red <- filter(onom_freq,
                        !str_detect(onomatopoeia, ",|-| |'|\\."))

# How many are left?

onom_freq_red
## # A tibble: 2,586  4
##    onomatopoeia     n unmarked_freq has_unmarked                   
##    <chr>        <int>         <dbl> <chr>                          
##  1 chip            75            68 occurs typographically unmarked
##  2 tsip            44             0 no unmarked                    
##  3 whit            32             0 no unmarked

##  5 chuck           24             1 occurs typographically unmarked
##  6 chirrup         23             4 occurs typographically unmarked
##  7 churr           23             0 no unmarked                    
##  8 seep            23             0 no unmarked                    
##  9 tsee            23             0 no unmarked                    
## 10 pik             22             0 no unmarked                    
## #  2,576 more rows

Model whether it occurs unmarked as a function of its frequency in the marked version:

onom_freq_red <- mutate(onom_freq_red,
                        has_unmarked = factor(has_unmarked, levels = c('no unmarked', 'occurs typographically unmarked')))

# Fit logistic regression model:

unmarked_mdl <- brm(has_unmarked ~ 1 + log(n),
                    data = onom_freq_red,
                    family = bernoulli,
                    
                    # MCMC settings:
                    
                    chains = 4, iter = 4000, warmup = 2000,
                    cores = 4, init = 0)

# Save:

save(unmarked_mdl, file = '../models/unmarked_mdl.RData')

load('../models/unmarked_mdl.RData')

6.2 Frequency and sentence position

See whether more frequent ones also occur in more or less isolated positions. To make some sense of this, well simplify lump the separated ones (after comma, semicolon, and colon) together, as well as all the within-sentence ones, for which well exclude the ones that start the sentence for now as we havent checked yet whether a comma or dot follows.

# Vectors for matching:

isolated <- c('after colon', 'after comma', 'after hyphen',
              'after semicolon')
collapse <- c('in brackets', 'starts sentence')

# Match and create new variable pre_iso_red:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     pre_iso_red = if_else(pre_isolation %in% collapse, NA, pre_isolation),
                     pre_iso_red = if_else(pre_iso_red %in% isolated, 'isolated', pre_iso_red))

Count by onomatopoeia and this new variable, after excluding NAs:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_iso_red)) |> 
  count(onomatopoeia, pre_iso_red, sort = TRUE) |> 
  group_by(onomatopoeia) |> 
  mutate(p = n / sum(n)) |> 
  slice_tail(n = 100) |> 
  print(n = Inf)

7 Frequency of syllables

7.1 Prep

Create a unique identifier variable that codes for the individual onomatopoeia:

onoms_long <- mutate(onoms_long,
                     onom_id = str_c(unique_id, ':', onomatopoeia))

Split the data up by syllable:

# Exclude NAs first:

onom_sylls <- filter(onoms_long,
                      !is.na(onomatopoeia))

# Lowercase:

onom_sylls <- mutate(onom_sylls,
                      onomatopoeia = str_to_lower(onomatopoeia))

# Reduce to relevant columns:

onom_sylls <- select(onom_sylls, unique_id, onom_id, onomatopoeia)

# Split up by special characters:

onom_sylls <- onom_sylls  |> 
  mutate(syllable = str_split(onomatopoeia,
                                  "[-'\".,;!?(){}\\[\\]<>/|@#$%^&*_+=`~:\\s]+")) |> 
  unnest(cols = c(syllable)) |> 
  filter(syllable != '')

# Get rid of empties:

onom_sylls <- onom_sylls |>
  filter(syllable != '')

# Show:

onom_sylls
## # A tibble: 20,462  4
##    unique_id onom_id                  onomatopoeia     syllable
##    <chr>     <chr>                    <chr>            <chr>   
##  1 id_2369   id_2369:hooweet          hooweet          hooweet 
##  2 id_5273   id_5273:gredek gredek... gredek gredek... gredek  
##  3 id_5273   id_5273:gredek gredek... gredek gredek... gredek  
##  4 id_1098   id_1098:krrarnk          krrarnk          krrarnk

7.2 Counts

What are the most frequent ones?

# Count:

sylls_count <- onom_sylls |> 
  count(syllable, sort = TRUE)

# Show:

sylls_count
## # A tibble: 5,598  2
##    syllable     n
##    <chr>    <int>
##  1 whit       216
##  2 chip       214
##  3 a          180
##  4 r          170
##  5 coo        154
##  6 kee        154
##  7 see        147
##  8 ti         137
##  9 wee        129
## 10 pee        128
## #  5,588 more rows

Lets now create a log frequency column of this:

sylls_count <- sylls_count |> 
  mutate(log_freq = log(n))

Do a left join:

full_with_component_freq <- onom_sylls |> 
  left_join(sylls_count) |> 
  group_by(onom_id) |> 
  summarize(component_freq = mean(log_freq))
## Joining with `by = join_by(syllable)`

Joint that back into onoms long:

onoms_long <- onoms_long |> 
  left_join(full_with_component_freq)
## Joining with `by = join_by(onom_id)`

Check:

select(onoms_long, unique_id, onom_id, onomatopoeia, component_freq)
## # A tibble: 11,356  4
##    unique_id onom_id                  onomatopoeia     component_freq

7.3 Syntactic position and component frequency

Check now whether this changes as a function of syntactic position:

onoms_long |> 
  group_by(pre_isolation) |> 
  summarize(M = mean(component_freq, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 8  2
##   pre_isolation       M
##   <chr>           <dbl>
## 1 after colon      2.33
## 2 after comma      2.17
## 3 after hyphen     1.95
## 4 after semicolon  1.80
## 5 in brackets      2.58
## 6 in sentence      2.04
## 7 starts sentence  2.32
## 8 <NA>             2.47

Make a plot of this:

onoms_long |> 
  filter(!is.na(pre_isolation)) |> 
  filter(pre_isolation != 'in brackets') |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(pre_isolation, component_freq), y = component_freq,
             fill = pre_isolation)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(direction = -1,
                    palette = 'YlGnBu') +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.6) +
  xlab(NULL) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        legend.position = 'none')
